06497nam a22009255i 9780814786451DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147864517 a10.18574/nyu/9780814786437.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547880  a(OCoLC)852158953  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE184.S69bS86 2016 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a304.87322304aThe Sun Never Sets :bSouth Asian Migrants in an Age of U.S. Power /ced. by Manu Vimalassery, Vivek Bald, Miabi Chatterji, Sujani Reddy. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource :b18 black and white illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNYU Series in Social and Cultural Analysis ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. OVERLAPPING EMPIRES -- t1 Intimate Dependency, Race, and Trans-Imperial Migration -- t2 Repressing the “Hindu Menace” -- t3 Desertion and Sedition -- t4 “The Hidden Hand” -- tPART II. FROM IMPERIALISM TO FREE-MARKET FUNDAMENTALISM -- t5 Putting “the Family” to Work -- t6 Looking Home -- t7 India’s Global and Internal Labor Migration and Resistance -- t8 Water for Life, Not for Coca-Cola -- t9 When an Interpreter Could Not Be Found -- tPART III. GEOGRAPHIES OF MIGRATION, SETTLEMENT, AND SELF -- t10 Intertwined Violence -- t11 Who’s Your Daddy? -- t12 Awaiting the Twelfth Imam in the United States -- t13 Tracing the Muslim Body -- t14 Antecedents of Imperial Incarceration -- tAfterword -- tIndex -- tAbout the Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Sun Never Sets collects the work of a generation of scholars who are enacting a shift in the orientation of the field of South Asian American studies. By focusing upon the lives, work, and activism of specific, often unacknowledged, migrant populations, the contributors present a more comprehensive vision of the South Asian presence in the United States.Tracking the changes in global power that have influenced the paths and experiences of migrants, from expatriate Indian maritime workers at the turn of the century, to Indian nurses during the Cold War, to post-9/11 detainees and deportees caught in the crossfire of the "War on Terror," these essays reveal how the South Asian diaspora has been shaped by the contours of U.S. imperialism. Driven by a shared sense of responsibility among the contributing scholars to alter the profile of South Asian migrants in the American public imagination, they address the key issues that impact these migrants in the U.S., on the subcontinent, and in circuits of the transnational economy. Taken together, these essays provide tools with which to understand the contemporary political and economic conjuncture and the place of South Asian migrants within it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aImmigrantsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBald, Vivek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBald, Vivek, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChatterji, Miabi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChatterji, Miabi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCiafone, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGopinath, Gayatri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasan, Farah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMir, Raza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMohaiemen, Naeem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb